  <h2>Valley Center's Market: Genuinely Rural with Commuter Appeal</h2>
  <p>Valley Center is 15 miles north of Wichita, genuinely rural feel but close enough to commute for Wichita work. Sedgwick County, about 7,500 people. This is not suburbs — it's actual rural character. You get small-town homes, rural acreage, bigger lots, properties with outbuildings. The commute to Boeing or Koch Industries in Wichita is maybe 30 minutes. That attracts people who want country living but still work in the city.</p>
  <p>Valley Center sellers are often rural property owners, farmers, agricultural families, or people who thought they wanted rural life but decided they'd rather be closer to town.</p>

  <h2>Valley Center Housing and Market</h2>
  <p>Valley Center is genuinely rural. Small-town homes mixed with rural acreage and properties with land. $120k-$250k typical for town homes, acreage properties vary widely. You get larger lots, bigger properties, potentially outbuildings, barns, or hobby farm situations. Different from suburbs — this is actual country living. Agricultural roots run deep here, and that affects the market.</p>
  <p>The market's quieter and less transient than Wichita suburbs. Longer holding periods for sales, but when someone's ready to sell, they often need actual solutions, not just listing services.</p>

  <h2>Who I Buy From in Valley Center</h2>
  <p>Rural property owners tired of managing land. Farmers selling acreage or family properties. Agricultural families aging out and needing to exit. Commuters who thought rural life was for them but realized they'd rather be closer to town. Estate sales from longtime agricultural families. People inheriting rural properties from parents who farmed or ranched. Hobby farm owners who underestimated the work involved.</p>

